The chief representative of the Eleatio School is Parmenides (b. 515 aa). He disengaged the doctrine of Xenophanes from its theologica] form, and ascribed to Being what his predecessor had ascribed to God His philosophy is the antithesis of that of Heraclitus. While Heraclitus said all is motion and change, the appearance of fixity is merely illusion of the senses3 Parmenides asserted, with distinct reference to him, that all that exists has existed and will exist the same for ever, that it is change and multiplicity which is illusory. Itis only by thought we can become conscious of the really existent 3 being and thought are the same, senso can only give rise to uncertain opinion In such language we see partly a protest against the vagueness of the conception of development or ‘becoming,' by which the Ionio philosophers en· deavoured to explain the origin of things, ‘You say fire becomes water, but each thing is what it is, and can never be otherwise 3' partly an idea of the indestructibility of matter, partly an antici- pation of the later distinction between necessary and contingent truth 3 thus one point dwelt upon by him was the impossibility of any separation of parts of space.
